      - tcp/ip advantage and disadvantage 
       - advantage 
        Perfect! Letâ€™s break TCP (Transmission Control Protocol) down in a simple, clear way â€” advantages and disadvantages.

ğŸ”¹ TCP Advantages âœ…

Reliable Delivery

TCP ensures all packets arrive complete and in order.

Lost packets are retransmitted automatically.

Connection-Oriented

Establishes a connection before sending data (3-way handshake).

Ensures both sender and receiver are ready.

Flow Control

Prevents sender from overwhelming receiver.

Uses windowing mechanism.

Error Detection & Correction

Each segment has checksum.

Errors are detected and corrected via retransmission.

Segmentation and Reassembly

Large data is broken into smaller segments.

Receiver reassembles them in order.

Multiplexing

Multiple applications can share one connection using port numbers.


  
  
  
  ğŸ”¹ TCP Disadvantages âŒ

Slower than UDP

Due to reliability checks, flow control, and handshake overhead.

Overhead

TCP headers are larger (20 bytes minimum), adds extra bits to each segment.

Connection Setup Required

3-way handshake adds latency before data transfer starts.

Resource Intensive

Needs memory and processing at both ends to track connections and state.

